A 1973 article entitled “The Behavior of Stock Prices on Fridays and Mondays” published in the Financial Analysts Journal claimed that stock returns are lower on Fridays than on Mondays. Some theories were proposed to explain the article's finding and the effect eventually disappeared in the data. Suppose, however, that everyone knew on Friday that the stock price would fall on Monday. Everyone should go [short] the stock until the price [equals] the expected Monday price.

A k-day moving average is the average price over the last k-days (the 50-day moving average is the average price over the last 50 trading days, the 200-day moving average is the average price over the last 200 trading days, etc.). They are called "moving" averages because they move from one time window to the next (at some point, 2020-01-01 will no longer be in the 200-day moving average). Technicians claim that one should buy a stock when the 50-day moving average crosses above the 200-day moving average (this is known as the "Golden Cross"). Given what you have learned about the Efficient Market Hypothesis, one could make money on average by [selling] a stock whenever it features a Golden Cross.

